'''Edward Carey''' (born April 1970, in North Walsham, Norfolk, England)<ref>Author's Website [https://edwardcareyauthor.com/about/]</ref> is a playwright, and novelist. He has written several adaptations for the stage, including [[Patrick Süskind]]’s ''The Pigeon'', and [[Robert Coover]]’s ''Pinocchio in Venice''. His own plays include ''Sulking Thomas'' and ''Captain of the Birds''. He collaborated with Eddin Khoo, on the ''[[wayang kulit]]'' translation of ''Macbeth'' called ''Macbeth in the Shadows''.<ref>Bakar, Sharon (19 June 2005) [http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=/2005/6/19/features/11239908&sec=features ''Writer who draws out books''], ''The Star'' (Malaysia){{dead link|date=October 2018}}</ref>

He attended the [[University of Iowa]] [[International Writing Program]] and taught at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]]. He is married to the writer [[Elizabeth McCracken]].<ref>[http://www.radcliffe.edu/research/fellows_2009emccracken.aspx ''2008–2009 Radcliffe Institute Fellows'']{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study, Harvard University{{dead link|date=October 2018}}</ref>

He is represented by Isobel Dixon at Blake Friedman.<ref>[http://www.blakefriedmann.co.uk/bookClients/_325/ ''Edward Carey''], Blake Friedman {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822000536/http://www.blakefriedmann.co.uk/bookClients/_325/ |date=22 August 2007 }}</ref>

==Reviews==
<blockquote>"Though Edward Carey seems to intend his first novel, Observatory Mansions, to be an unsentimental, surrealist romance, it's really a paean to loneliness. For the book is never so interesting as when its characters are despairing and alone. All goes well then for the first hundred pages, where Carey lays out the solitude housed in Observatory Mansions, a greying apartment building where Francis Orme, the book's narrator, cultivates a secret life of stillness and theft."<ref>Valdes, Marcela (18 April 2001). [http://www.citypages.com/2001-04-18/books/edward-carey-observatory-mansions/ ''Edward Carey: Observatory Mansions''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606031539/http://www.citypages.com/2001-04-18/books/edward-carey-observatory-mansions/ |date=6 June 2011 }}, ''Minneapolis City Pages''</ref></blockquote>

<blockquote>"From Richardson to Dickens to Ackroyd, English literary fiction seems to favour the elephantine. Miniaturists – Austen, Pym perhaps, Brookner – are rarer, less typical. Edward Carey is most decidedly a miniaturist. "Miniature things move people," he remarks, two dozen pages into his second novel; and again, a similar distance from the end."<ref>Greenland, Colin (17 May 2003). [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/may/17/featuresreviews.guardianreview22 "Small world"], ''The Guardian''</ref></blockquote>

<blockquote>"An imaginary city: this is a time for such a vision, especially for New Yorkers, whose city has always been in flux, though perhaps never more painfully and self-consciously than today. Entralla, the fictitious metropolis at the heart of Edward Carey's second novel, exists not only in our imagination and in the pages of ''Alva & Irva'' (which serves as Entralla's one and only guidebook) but in the form of tiny plasticine models of its streets and houses, seen in the appealingly smudgy photographs that punctuate the novel. A re-creation of Entralla also appears in the story of ''Alva & Irva,'' since the twins of the book's title are the designer and sculptor, respectively, of their native city in miniature."<ref>Harrison, Carey (23 March 2003). [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B06E7DA113EF930A15750C0A9659C8B63 ''One Word: Plasticine''], ''The New York Times''</ref></blockquote>

